[2026-07-04T13:05:00] TASK 1D — PIVOT
Two architectural calls made explicit rather than silently decided:
1. `Paper.display_abstract` (Task 1A schema) is a flat string with no
   room to store PubMed's per-section `Label` metadata (§7.5's structured
   abstracts). Since this task is the single source of truth for section-
   header vs. sentence segmentation, `tokenize.py`'s public
   `build_segmented_abstract()` takes structured input directly — a
   `list[AbstractSection(label: str | None, text: str)]`, one entry per
   EFetch `<AbstractText>` element (or a single `label=None` entry for an
   unstructured abstract) — and *also* returns the flattened
   `display_abstract` string for whichever task persists `Paper` rows
   (Task 3A, per 1B's own log) to store. Flagging this so 3A/1B know the
   flattening decision (how headers and section breaks are joined into
   one string) lives here, not reimplemented at the persistence call site.
2. Real MEDLINE `Language` field values are 3-letter codes (e.g. "eng",
   "fre"), not BCP-47 — SPEC.md §13.3 doesn't spell this out, but this is
   the actual PubMed/MEDLINE record format. `is_narration_unavailable()`
   maps the common MEDLINE 3-letter codes to a 2-letter subtag before
   comparing against the active narration locale's base language (e.g.
   "en-US" -> "en"), and treats a missing/unrecognized `language` value
   permissively (`narration_unavailable=False`) rather than blocking
   narration on absent data, since §13.3 says the check only applies
   "when present."
3. Used a small self-written `_spell_cardinal()` (0 to 999,999) in
   `normalize.py` instead of adding a `num2words` dependency — avoids
   touching the shared `pyproject.toml` (a file this task doesn't own)
   for a narrow amount of integer-spelling this abstract-narration use
   case actually needs.

