[2026-07-04T16:05:00] TASK 3C — PIVOT (post-adversarial-review fix)
Adversarial review (logs/adversarial-generalist.build.log, "TASK 3C
REVIEW") found a real, reproducible bypass in
`_neutralize_formula_injection`: it checked `value.startswith(("=", "+",
"-", "@"))` on the raw string with no handling for leading whitespace or
invisible Unicode format characters first. Confirmed directly —
`_neutralize_formula_injection("\t=1+1")`, `(" =1+1")`, and
`("‮=1+1")` (a leading RTL-override character) all returned
unchanged/unneutralized. Real exploitability: some spreadsheet CSV
importers strip leading whitespace/invisible characters themselves
before evaluating a formula trigger, so a PubMed title like `"\t=1+1"`
would flow through this endpoint unmodified yet still be interpreted as
a live formula on open in such an importer — the importer's notion of
"first character" disagreed with Python's raw string indexing, and the
importer's notion is what actually matters here.
