Adversarial review (logs/adversarial-generalist.build.log, "LIVE-TEST
FIX: DB SCHEMA REVIEW") found no blocking issues — confirmed the fix
itself is real and correctly wired by independently reading
SQLAlchemy's `create_all` source. Flagged two SIGNIFICANT but doc-only
gaps, explicitly not requiring a code/test change:

1. Undocumented TOCTOU race under concurrent first boot: `create_all`'s
   checkfirst logic is `has_table()` then a plain `CREATE TABLE` as two
   unsynchronized steps (no `IF NOT EXISTS`, no shared transaction) — two
   processes booting `lifespan` concurrently against a genuinely EMPTY
   database (overlapping rolling-redeploy instances, or 2+ replicas
   cold-starting together) could race, with the loser hitting an
   unhandled `OperationalError`. Harmless against the current production
   Turso DB (tables already exist, so it's a no-op now) but a real
   landmine for any future fresh-environment multi-replica first boot.
2. Undocumented ALTER-TABLE limitation: `create_all` only compares table
   NAMES, never diffs columns — adding a field to an existing
   `entities.py` model later will silently not propagate to an
   already-existing table, reproducing this exact bug class (missing
   column instead of missing table) one schema change from now. No
   migration tool exists in this project's scope (confirmed by my own
   earlier grep of SPEC.md/BuildPlan.md, independently re-confirmed by
   the reviewer).

Added a doc comment directly on the `lifespan`/`create_all` call in
`backend/app/main.py` spelling out both limitations in full, so a
future developer doesn't assume `create_all` is a complete migration
solution or is safe under concurrent first-boot — no behavioral change,
comment-only.

